The members are working within a fixed budget, the AMA says, so they keep each other in check: if the RUC votes to raise the RVU of one procedure, it has to account for that increase by decreasing RVUs of other procedures elsewhere. And that’s true—as far as it goes. The process does indeed involve much squabbling among specialist societies, and RUC representatives do sometimes end up voting to lower codes that would positively affect their own societies. “There’s a certain calculation that happens, and people definitely vote against themselves,” a former RUC member told me.
